      <h2>Signs Your Liverpool Boiler Needs Replacing</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">If your boiler is over 10 years old or showing any of these signs, a replacement is worth considering seriously.</p>
      <div class="pf-signs" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Boiler is over 10 to 12 years old</strong><p>Modern A-rated condensing boilers operate at 90 to 94% efficiency. A boiler installed before 2010 typically runs at 65 to 70%. Replacing it is almost always more cost-effective than continuing to repair it.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Repair bills are mounting up</strong><p>If you are spending more than £200 to £300 per year on boiler repairs, a replacement will almost certainly pay for itself within a few years. A new boiler at £1,800 compares very favourably to years of escalating repair costs.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Boiler breaks down when it is most needed</strong><p>If your boiler fails during cold snaps, the heat exchanger or other internal components are likely failing. Older boilers struggle most when demand is highest. A boiler showing warning signs in summer will fail in the first cold snap of autumn.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Energy bills rising without explanation</strong><p>A boiler losing efficiency burns more gas to produce the same heat output. If your bills are rising but your usage has not changed, your boiler is working harder than it should.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Strange noises from the boiler</strong><p>Banging, kettling, whistling or gurgling sounds indicate internal problems. In an older boiler these often signal that replacement is more economical than repair.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Pilot light keeps going out</strong><p>On older boilers a pilot light that keeps extinguishing usually indicates a thermocouple failure or carbon deposit build-up. In a boiler over 10 years old this is a strong indicator that replacement is the right decision.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Yellow or orange flame instead of blue</strong><p>A healthy gas flame is blue. Yellow or orange indicates incomplete combustion and a potential carbon monoxide risk. Stop using the boiler immediately and call a <a href="https://www.gassaferegister.co.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Gas Safe registered</a> engineer. If you suspect a gas emergency, call <a href="https://cadentgas.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Cadent Gas on 0800 111 999</a> first.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>EPC rating of F or G</strong><p>An old inefficient boiler is the primary cause of a poor Energy Performance Certificate rating. A new A-rated boiler is the single biggest step towards improving your EPC, which can add a further 14% to property value and is increasingly required by mortgage lenders. See the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/check-energy-performance-certificate" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GOV.UK EPC checker</a>.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign" style="border-left-color:var(--red);"><div><strong>No Gas Safe certificate on record</strong><p>If your boiler has no certificate on record you have no evidence it was installed correctly or legally. A replacement gives you a fully documented, compliant installation with a Benchmark certificate and Gas Safe certificate issued on the same day.</p></div></div>
      </div>

