      <h2>Boiler Installation in Liverpool's Older Properties</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">Liverpool has one of the highest concentrations of Victorian and Edwardian housing in England. Our engineers have 30 years experience with every type of Liverpool property.</p>

      <div class="pf-card pf-card-navy" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <h3>What Makes Liverpool Properties Different</h3>
        <p>Many of Liverpool's Victorian terraces, Georgian townhouses and Edwardian semis were built with gravity-fed heating systems, back boilers behind fires, chimneys used as flue routes and pipework configurations that differ significantly from modern builds. Areas including Aigburth, Allerton, Sefton Park, Mossley Hill, Crosby and Woolton have particularly high concentrations of these older property types.</p>
        <p>A boiler installer without specific Liverpool experience can underestimate the complexity of these installations and either quote incorrectly or fit the wrong system. Our engineers have been working in Liverpool's housing stock since the 1990s. We know which problems to anticipate before we open a wall. The free survey visit is essential for any older Liverpool property. We identify complications before they become surprises on installation day.</p>
        <p>For further information on gas installation safety requirements in older properties, see <a href="https://www.hse.gov.uk/gas/domestic/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HSE domestic gas safety guidance</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="pf-card pf-card-orange" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <h3>Can I Install My Own Boiler?</h3>
        <p>No. It is illegal to install a gas boiler yourself unless you are Gas Safe registered. All gas boiler work, including installation, replacement and certain repair tasks, must be carried out by a <a href="https://www.gassaferegister.co.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Gas Safe registered engineer</a>. An incorrectly installed boiler is a serious risk of carbon monoxide poisoning, gas leaks and fire. Always verify your engineer's Gas Safe registration number before any gas work is carried out. See <a href="https://www.hse.gov.uk/gas/domestic/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HSE guidance on domestic gas safety</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

